  },
  {
    question: 'How often should CPU and GPU thermal paste be replaced?',
    answer:
      'Most thermal compounds last 3-5 years before they dry out and lose effectiveness. If your PC is older than that, or you’re seeing CPU/GPU temperatures 10°C+ higher than when it was new, a repaste will usually drop temps significantly. High-end pastes like Thermal Grizzly Kryonaut last longer; cheap stock paste can dry out in 2 years.',
  },
  {
    question: 'My gaming PC keeps shutting down during games — is it overheating?',
    answer:
      'Almost certainly yes. Modern CPUs and GPUs throttle around 90-95°C and the system will hard-shut-down at around 105°C to protect the silicon. If you’re getting random reboots or shutdowns specifically during demanding games or on hot days, overheating is the most likely cause. Dust buildup, dried thermal paste, failing fans, or degraded coolant are the usual culprits.',
  },
  {
    question: 'Can you service a custom water-cooled PC in Romford?',
    answer:
      'Yes — I service custom open-loop and AIO water-cooled PCs in Harold Hill, Romford and across the Havering area. That includes draining and flushing the loop, replacing coolant, checking for leaks, replacing CPU and GPU thermal paste, dust cleaning, and re-testing temperatures. Bring it in or I can collect locally.',
  },
  {
    question: 'What temperatures should my gaming PC run at?',
    answer:
      'Idle: CPU 30-45°C, GPU 30-50°C. Under gaming load: CPU should stay under 80°C, GPU under 75°C for healthy long-term operation. Spikes to the mid-80s are fine, but sustained 90°C+ means something is wrong — usually airflow, dust, paste, or coolant.',
  },
